WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.440
Hi everyone, my name is Sarah Altman and I'm on the developer relations team at Posit.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:12.700
Thanks for coming to this workflow demo.

00:00:12.700 --> 00:00:19.719
At the end of the session, there will be a live Q&A, at which point you can ask any questions.

00:00:19.719 --> 00:00:23.600
Today I'm going to talk about connecting Shiny apps to databases with Posit Team.

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:29.260
I'll show you an example app that can read from and write back to a DuckDB database,

00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:32.619
and I'll show you that app in both R and Python.

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:36.740
I'm going to focus on how the app connects to and reads from the database, allows users

00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:41.299
to edit a table, and then writes those changes back to the database.

00:00:41.299 --> 00:00:45.980
I'll also talk about considerations for deploying your app, and show you how to deploy to Posit

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:46.980
Connect.

00:00:46.980 --> 00:00:49.099
So let's get started.

00:00:49.099 --> 00:00:53.419
So before we take a look at the app, let's first talk about why you would even want to

00:00:53.419 --> 00:00:57.639
connect your Shiny app to a database.

00:00:57.639 --> 00:01:02.400
One reason is that your organization might just store your data in a database, and you

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:07.959
want to make a Shiny app that interacts with, displays, does something with that data.

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:10.080
A second consideration is speed.

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:14.839
Even if your data originates elsewhere, you can use DuckDB to speed up operations, which

00:01:14.839 --> 00:01:20.879
might be important if your app allows the user to do a lot of computations on the data.

00:01:20.879 --> 00:01:25.559
A third reason is if your app's functionality relies on a shared data source.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:29.599
As you'll see, the app we'll build today allows users to read and write to a central

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:33.279
data source.

00:01:33.279 --> 00:01:35.720
So let's talk about the general workflow.

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:40.400
We're going to create an app that reads from a DuckDB database, allows users to edit that

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:48.040
data by flagging suspicious values, and then writes those flagged values back to the database.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:53.199
As I said, we're going to use a DuckDB database, but the code we'll write can be adapted to

00:01:53.199 --> 00:01:57.959
a variety of database management systems.

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:03.279
This related blog post linked here shows the same code we'll see today adapted for Snowflake

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:07.199
and Databricks.

00:02:07.199 --> 00:02:10.039
So let's take a look at the app.

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:13.000
This is the app that we'll be working on today.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.300
I've written the same app in both R and Python, and the GitHub repositories are linked below.

00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:23.460
This is an image of the Python app, but the R one looks pretty similar.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:29.059
The general idea of this app is to allow users to flag suspicious values in a dataset.

00:02:29.059 --> 00:02:35.339
That data is displayed in the plot on the left-hand side with a few outliers highlighted,

00:02:35.339 --> 00:02:39.380
and then those outliers are displayed in that table on the right-hand side.

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:43.419
You can edit the flag column if you think a value might be an error or is in some way

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:51.300
suspicious, and then write those flag values back to the database, at which point the idea

00:02:51.300 --> 00:02:57.020
is maybe someone would take a closer look at those rows of data or exclude suspicious

00:02:57.020 --> 00:02:59.059
values or something like that.

00:02:59.059 --> 00:03:05.539
So we're not really changing the underlying data, but we're just adding a flag.

00:03:05.539 --> 00:03:09.020
Now let's take a look at the deployed version of the app so we can see it in action and

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:12.820
interact with it.

00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:16.460
So now we're looking at the deployed version of the app.

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:18.580
So let's see how it works.

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:22.880
On the left-hand side, we have this plot that's displaying the data.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:27.899
This is error quality data, so it's showing the date and the PPM, which is the ozone level

00:03:27.899 --> 00:03:31.419
in parts per million on that date.

00:03:31.419 --> 00:03:35.619
In blue are a couple of highlighted outlying values.

00:03:35.619 --> 00:03:42.000
So you can click on these values, and the corresponding row will highlight in this table.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.240
This is an editable table, which means that you can edit this value.

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:50.639
And when we talk about the code in a minute, I'll show you how to implement that in your

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:51.639
Shiny app.

00:03:51.639 --> 00:03:56.440
I'm going to change this back.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:04:01.279
The point of the flag is if you identify a point that you think is not just an outlier

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:07.119
but is suspicious in some way, you think it's an error, something went wrong, you can set

00:04:07.119 --> 00:04:13.600
the flag to 1 just to mark that there might be a problem with that row of data.

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:22.160
And then you can click write to database to write that flag back to the database table.

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:29.320
And one other thing I want to highlight, as it says down here, this example app is reading

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:34.839
from and writing to an in-memory DuckDB database, which means that when you refresh the page,

00:04:34.839 --> 00:04:37.839
the database is going to be regenerated from scratch.

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:41.200
So you're not going to see any changes that you have written.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:43.519
This is solely for the purposes of the example.

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:47.040
Obviously, this isn't really how you would want to implement this in real life, since

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:51.399
you would want those updated flag values to persist.

00:04:51.399 --> 00:04:58.160
But for the purposes of the example, to make it so that it's not confusing if someone else

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:01.920
who is using the app has changed the flags, but you don't know that they're using the

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:08.399
app, and so you're wondering why suddenly all your flag values have been updated.

00:05:08.399 --> 00:05:11.720
This doesn't really change any of the code that we're going to talk about today, but

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:14.720
this is just something to keep in mind.

