00:20:34.959 --> 00:20:39.959
And Posit Connect will automatically provide the correct values to your app during runtime.

00:20:40.959 --> 00:20:47.959
So say our database had a key that controlled access.

00:20:48.959 --> 00:20:54.959
We can add a var called dbKey.

00:20:55.959 --> 00:20:58.959
And then add the value of that key.

00:21:00.959 --> 00:21:01.959
Add the variable.

00:21:05.959 --> 00:21:06.959
Click Save.

00:21:07.959 --> 00:21:15.959
And then in our app, we would then, in the Connection code,

00:21:16.959 --> 00:21:19.959
reference that value.

00:21:20.959 --> 00:21:21.959
So we do.

00:21:29.959 --> 00:21:31.959
That's the password.

00:21:33.959 --> 00:21:37.959
And then we would add a var called dbKey.

00:21:38.959 --> 00:21:42.959
And then we would add a var called dbKey.

00:21:42.959 --> 00:21:44.959
That's the password.

00:21:47.959 --> 00:21:55.959
And now when we deploy the app, it'll get that value from Connect and be able to manage access that way.

00:21:58.959 --> 00:22:04.959
So as you just saw, one way to deploy your app and manage access involves using environment variables in Posit Connect.

00:22:05.959 --> 00:22:09.959
This strategy relies on adding one set of credentials to Posit Connect, though.

00:22:10.959 --> 00:22:13.959
What if you want each user to authenticate with their own credentials?

00:22:14.959 --> 00:22:19.959
This could be particularly important if your database includes row-level or data-level permissions.

00:22:20.959 --> 00:22:26.959
One solution is to use OAuth integration, which is now available in Posit Connect for Databricks and Snowflake,

00:22:27.959 --> 00:22:29.959
allowing users to log in with their own accounts.

00:22:30.959 --> 00:22:34.959
With OAuth integration, you don't need to specify the database credentials used in your app.

00:22:34.959 --> 00:22:40.959
Instead, users can authenticate through the OAuth integration, and then Posit Connect will automatically handle the connection.

00:22:41.959 --> 00:22:48.959
For other database management systems, you can request user credentials through your app and then pass those credentials to the connection code.

00:22:51.959 --> 00:22:54.959
So now just to summarize what we talked about today,

00:22:55.959 --> 00:22:59.959
you saw how to create a shiny app that reads from and writes to a database.

00:22:59.959 --> 00:23:04.959
We used IBIS for the Python app to build a connection to DuckDB and read in a table.

00:23:05.959 --> 00:23:09.959
For the R version of the app, we used the DBI package for the same task.

00:23:10.959 --> 00:23:17.959
Then, to allow users of the app to make changes to the data, we created an editable table that lets you set a flag value.

00:23:18.959 --> 00:23:22.959
We then wrote the changes made by the user back to our original database table.

00:23:22.959 --> 00:23:28.959
And then we deployed the app to Posit Connect and discussed two possible ways to securely deploy your app.

00:23:31.959 --> 00:23:38.959
I showed you one particular implementation of this style of app, an app that reads in data from a database, displays it,

00:23:39.959 --> 00:23:43.959
allows someone to edit that data, and then writes the data back to the database.

00:23:44.959 --> 00:23:47.959
But you can imagine this framework extending to other use cases,

00:23:47.959 --> 00:23:51.959
such as labeling images when training an image recognition system or something similar.

